Q. What is CSS Specificity?
A. CSS Specificity is the set of rules the browser uses to determine 
    which CSS rule should be applied when multiple rules target the same element.
    suppose : <p id="title" class="text">Hello World</p>
    p {
      color: blue;
    }    
    .text {
      color: green;
    }    
    #title {
      color: red;
    }
    here 3 color is present but id has higher Specificity, so color will be red.
    | Selector                                                             |                                  Specificity |
    | -------------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------: |
    | Universal `*`                                                        |                                            0 |
    | Element (`p`, `div`, `h1`)                                           |                                            1 |
    | Class (`.box`), Attribute (`[type="text"]`), Pseudo-class (`:hover`) |                                           10 |
    | ID (`#header`)                                                       |                                          100 |
    | Inline style (`style=""`)                                            |                                         1000 |
    | `!important`                                                         | Overrides normal specificity (use sparingly) |
